  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Letter to Park, the Attendant Censor
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, Lee, Vice Director of the Imperial Stables and Keeper of the Literary Repository, respectfully address this letter to you, esteemed Park.

    When people truly know one another, they cherish knowing each other's hearts. Throughout my life, though many have claimed to know me, few have truly understood my spirit. Only the late Minister Eom possessed that rare attunement—a harmony so profound it needed no words to be grasped.

    During Minister Eom's lifetime, he had a friend named Lee Ki, a man of singular gifts. He was especially skilled at portraiture and painted Minister Eom's likeness with remarkable fidelity. The Minister would show me the portrait three times over, clearly hoping I would inscribe it with verse. I lacked the courage to comply.

    Recently, visiting your home by chance, I beheld that portrait once more. As I bowed before it, I seemed to see the Minister as he was in life—his countenance serene and luminous in repose. Whether approaching him at court or catching his likeness from afar, his expression conveyed such vitality—his face glowed with presence, his eyes and brows so expressive that he seemed about to speak or smile. Between each glance, tears fell unbidden. You graciously allowed me to borrow it, and I brought it home to hang upon my wall. For days I rose and bowed before it as I would before Buddha or Bodhisattva, my heart overflowing with memories until sobs choked my words.

    For writing springs from feeling, and when the heart is stirred, expression cannot be contained. Thus moved, I gathered these meager words into praise—though at first I wished to write abundantly of Minister Eom's achievements. Yet the space above the portrait being so narrow, I was forced to count each character carefully, cutting and cutting again until only this brief inscription remained.

    Alas, Minister Eom was among heaven's greatest men—his talents vast and bold, his bearing generous and open-hearted, his wisdom in both civil and military affairs brilliant as clear sky. Though one exhausted all the bamboo of South Mountain, one could not capture his full measure, much less within this modest frame. How could I hope to limn him comprehensively in so small a space?

    Yet I fear that after a hundred generations, as time stretches long and colors fade, even distant descendants may forget whose visage this is. How much less would strangers know? This is why I inscribe these words—to leave some mark for posterity. Though my writing may not fully satisfy you, it was written with the hope of endurance, with no shallow purpose.

    Should you ever view it, perhaps it might offer some comfort to your grief. Yet I cannot presume to know your thoughts on this matter.

    With respectful reverence, I remain your humble servant.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Minister Eom' (嚴尙書) referenced appears to be a significant historical figure with whom the author shared a spiritual kinship.
    - The metaphorical language about 'wind-moved feet' and precise measurement reflects the Buddhist and Confucian literary aesthetics of Goryeo.
    - The comparison of viewing the portrait to venerating Buddhist images reflects the syncretistic spiritual practices of the Goryeo period.
